    "pathophysiology": "Elevated right heart pressure transmits to hepatic veins causing sinusoidal congestion. This leads to centrilobular hepatocyte necrosis (zone 3 is most vulnerable to hypoxia). Pericellular fibrosis develops over time, eventually causing true bridging fibrosis and cirrhosis (cardiac cirrhosis). Impaired bilirubin excretion from hepatocyte injury and canalicular dysfunction produces cholestatic jaundice. Severe acute hypotension causes ischemic hepatitis with massive AST/ALT rise.",
